# DevSecOps — OWASP Top 10

## Secure by Default

- Every route is **private** unless explicitly marked public.
- Passwords are **never** stored in plaintext. Use Argon2id or BCrypt with appropriate cost factors.
- Secrets and API keys go in environment variables, never in source code.

## Zero Trust Input Validation

- Validate **every** external input (request body, query params, headers) with Zod schemas.
- Use UUID v4/v7 for entity IDs to prevent IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference).
- Never trust client-side data for authorization decisions.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — sequential numeric IDs expose enumeration
id: serial('id').primaryKey()

// ✅ GOOD — UUIDs prevent IDOR
id: uuid('id').defaultRandom().primaryKey()
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — unvalidated input
app.post('/tenants', (req, res) => {
  db.insert(req.body);
});

// ✅ GOOD — Zod schema validation
const CreateTenantSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1).max(200),
  email: z.string().email(),
  document: z.string().regex(/^\d{11,14}$/),
});

app.post('/tenants', (req, res) => {
  const data = CreateTenantSchema.parse(req.body);
  // ...
});
```

## SAST / SCA

- Before suggesting `npm install <pkg>`, check for known vulnerabilities.
- Prefer packages with active maintenance, no critical CVEs, and minimal transitive dependencies.
- Flag any use of `eval()`, `innerHTML`, `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`, or unsanitized SQL interpolation.

## Auth & Session

- Use short-lived JWTs with refresh token rotation.
- Implement rate limiting on auth endpoints.
- Log authentication failures for anomaly detection.
